english:
  title: A Letter to Minister Pae Chan of the Ministry of Personnel
  author: Choi Chi-won
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I humbly hear that you have received the sovereign's favor with glory, and I bow in gratitude and consolation. Consider how in this age of luminous virtue, the realm seeks only to elevate the capable and worthy. The virtuous streams of talent all converge in selecting the true and discarding the false. Authority has already passed to those of great capability, and both ancient and modern times entrust themselves to superior minds. Where human hope finds accord, there the imperial grace resides.

    Your Excellency's heart stands distant from the dusty paths of office; your nature delights in the way of Tao. When the moon climbs high, cranes cry through the frost in measured notes; when clouds part, the lotus peaks rise ten thousand fathoms into view. Long ago you perceived fortune's reversal and withdrew from the clamor of the world. The blessed grasses and celestial flowers of Yangcheon nearly summoned the butterfly's dream; the dawn mists and evening vapors of Langyuan deepened the splendor of the tiger and leopard's form.

    Yet the potter's wheel cannot remain idle in the mountains, nor can the suffering world await a master elsewhere. Thus you laid aside your hermitage and came to court, ascending to the Ministry of Personnel's seat, fulfilling all the aspirations of the crowned and gowned. In former times when you presided over the examinations, you searched the mountains and seas until all seemed empty; today, in selecting talent, you judge the waters without their mingling. Where your clarity flows, confusion must cease. May you traverse the lofty ranks of the six provinces and at last fill the vacant seats of the Three Excellencies. From afar and near, morning and evening without end, I pray.

    I have long revered your immortal traces and from afar admired your noble form. My joy in gazing upon you knows no restraint, and my devotion finds no bounds.
  footnotes:
    - The 'Three Excellencies' (三台) refers to the highest ministerial positions in the imperial bureaucracy.
    - References to mountains, lotus peaks, and hermitage evoke the Daoist ideals of withdrawal from worldly affairs that Choi Chi-won admired.
    - The image of waters not mingling alludes to the famous passage about the Zi and Mian rivers, symbolizing clarity and discrimination in judgment.
